[{"module":{"title":"Anonymising Data","aim":"<p>The aim of this module is to equip learners with the knowledge and skills necessary to effectively manage and mitigate risks associated with handling and sharing personal data. Through practical examples and hands-on exercises, participants will learn to establish lawful and ethical bases for data projects, set clear objectives, assess risks, apply anonymisation techniques, and implement processes for monitoring and responding to existing and new risks.</p>","learningOutcomes":[{"outcome":"Demonstrate an understanding of the ethical and legal considerations surrounding the handling and sharing of personal data."},{"outcome":"Identify appropriate lawful bases for anonymising data."},{"outcome":"Develop clear objectives for the anonymising of data that balance maximising utility with minimising risk."},{"outcome":"Assess the potential risks associated with handling and sharing personal data, including the risk of re-identification and potential harm."},{"outcome":"Apply anonymisation techniques effectively to mitigate the risks and protect individual privacy while maintaining the utility of the data."},{"outcome":"Evaluate the resilience of anonymisation techniques through testing and validation procedures."},{"outcome":"Plan the publication of data while considering anonymisation details and risk assessments to ensure compliance with data protection regulations and ethical principles."},{"outcome":"Implement processes for monitoring and responding to existing and emerging risks associated with data handling and sharing."}],"reflectiveQuestions":[{"question":"Consider the data you handle about people. Do you share it? Who do you share it with? How do you share it? And, most importantly, how do you protect it?"},{"question":"Is there any data that you don’t handle because of the risks associated with it? Are there any anonymisation techniques that could be applied to ensure that the value of the data can be realised whilst minimising the risk to individuals?"},{"question":"What could be done better at your organisation to ensure utility is maintained and privacy protected? Why?"}]},"content":[{"block":{"title":"Anonymising Data","type":"Title"},"components":[{"body":"<p>There are many cases where you might need to use or share data containing personal or sensitive information about individuals. To reduce the risk of handling this personal data, you may need to apply anonymisation techniques.&nbsp;</p><p>So, how might you anonymise data?</p><p>This module looks at:</p><ul>\n<li>The 7 steps of anonymisation</li>\n<li>The role of synthetic data</li>\n<li>The relationship between anonymisation and data protection regulations</li>\n</ul>","properties":{"instruction":"","items":[]}},{"properties":{"instruction":"","items":[]}}]},{"block":{"title":"Anonymisation in 7-steps","type":"Title"},"components":[{"body":"<p>Generally speaking, there are 7-steps to the anonymisation process. Explore each of these below.</p>","properties":{"instruction":"","items":[]}}]},{"block":{"title":"STEP 1: Establish the lawful and ethical basis","type":"Title"},"components":[{"body":"<div class=\"heading-with-rule\"><p>Data Anonymisation &amp; Regulations</p></div><p>Once personal data is anonymised, meaning the risk of re-identification is sufficiently small, it is no longer subject to data protection regulations such as the GDPR or the UK Data Protection Act 2018.</p><div class=\"heading-with-rule\"><p>Pre-anonymisation Requirements</p></div><p>However, prior to anonymising personal data, you must assess the lawful and ethical basis for using it. If necessary, undertake a Privacy Impact Assessment - especially if the data you are using is special category data, meaning, sensitive data.</p><div class=\"heading-with-rule\"><p>Ethical Assessment</p></div><p>In addition to the lawful basis, it's crucial to carry out an ethical assessment on the impact of the anonymisation. This evaluation should weigh both the potential benefits and harms that might result.</p>","properties":{"instruction":"","items":[]}}]},{"block":{"title":"STEP 2: Set objectives","type":"Title"},"components":[{"body":"<div class=\"anonymisation-content\">\r\n\r\n    <div class=\"point\">\r\n                <p class=\"border-card-box\">Anonymisation should be done in a way that aims to maintain as much of the intended utility while also protecting privacy.</p>\r\n    </div>\r\n    \r\n    <div class=\"point\">\r\n                <p class=\"border-card-box\">In order to do this it is a good idea to outline some potential use cases. These should have already been considered during the legal and ethical evaluation in step 1.</p>\r\n    </div>\r\n\r\n    <div class=\"point\">\r\n                <p class=\"border-card-box\">At the end of this stage, you should know which objectives you are looking to support and which are out of scope due to legal or ethical concerns.</p>\r\n    </div>\r\n\r\n</div>","properties":{"instruction":"","items":[]}}]},{"block":{"title":"STEP 3: Assess risk","type":"Title"},"components":[{"body":"<p>It is important to understand that data protection does not require anonymisation to be completely risk free &ndash; you must be able to mitigate the risk of re-identification until it is sufficiently small.</p> <p>To do this, identify characteristics in your dataset that can directly or indirectly be used to identify a person: the personal data.&nbsp;</p> <p>Following this, you should determine which of these characteristics pose a potential threat to harm an individual and label them as either posing a &lsquo;normal&rsquo; or &lsquo;high&rsquo; risk.</p>","properties":{"instruction":"","items":[]}},{"properties":{"instruction":"","items":[]}}]},{"block":{"title":"STEP 4: Anonymise personal data","type":"Title"},"components":[{"body":"<p>There are several techniques that can be used to anonymise data. In the majority of cases, several techniques may need to be applied to lower the risks of re-identification. Regardless of the technique applied, we must:</p> <ul class=\"blue-caution-callout\"> <li>Choose the right combination of techniques will depend on both the intended use and the level of risk related to each characteristic in the dataset.</li> <li>Keep a record on how each technique is applied and the reasons for its choice.</li> </ul> <p>The EU Data Protection Working Party has produced a useful report outlining anonymisation techniques, robustness and typical mistakes. We have summarised these techniques in the later hands-on section of Anonymising Data.</p>","properties":{"instruction":"","items":[]}}]},{"block":{"title":"STEP 5: Testing resilience","type":"Title"},"components":[{"body":"<p><strong>Anonymisation Resilience Check</strong></p><p>Anonymisation is considered successful when the risk of re-identification is low. To test this, you should carry out resilience tests.</p><p>This step will also help you analyse the risk/utility balance. As before, stay safe and if you are worried, take a more cautious approach.</p><div class=\"callout\"><p>Ask Yourself:</p><ul><li>Is it possible to single out an individual?</li><li>Is it possible to link records relating to an individual using data already available?</li><li>Can information be inferred concerning an individual within the same dataset?</li></ul></div><p>You should also consider putting yourself in the shoes of a stakeholder who may have a nefarious interest in the dataset. You may have identified these stakeholders during the risk assessment when considering intentions of attackers. If you cannot think of any stakeholders, but you labelled data ‘high risk’, it could be that the risk is not as high risk as you first thought.</p><p><strong>Note:</strong> If you answered ‘yes’ to any of the questions, go back to Step 3.</p>","properties":{"instruction":"","items":[]}}]},{"block":{"title":"STEP 6: Write a plan to mitigate risk","type":"Title"},"components":[{"body":"<div class=\"heading-with-rule\"><p>Risk Management Plan</p></div><div class=\"two-item-grid-container\"><div class=\"callout\"><p>You should create a plan to monitor and handle any potential risks, for example when normal risks might require action.</p></div><div class=\"callout\"><p>Include roles and responsibilities that describe who does what in a given situation to help clarify the actions that need to be put in place in case of re-identification.</p></div></div><p>This plan should be shared with a data protection officer or other authority for them to review and decide if the methods and procedures you applied pose minimal risk to re-identification.</p>","properties":{"instruction":"","items":[]}}]},{"block":{"title":"STEP 7: Publish the data, anonymisation details and risk assessment","type":"Title"},"components":[{"body":"<p>Once the dataset is anonymised and risk of re-identification low, it can be shared/published for others to use.</p><p>In addition to the data, it is highly recommended that the following are also published</p><div class=\"padded-callout\"><p><strong>Recommended publications:</strong></p><ul><li>The objectives for your anonymisation</li><li>The techniques applied to anonymise the dataset</li><li>Your risk assessment</li><li>Your plan to mitigate risks</li><li>Details of how people can reach out with questions and concerns</li></ul></div>","properties":{"instruction":"","items":[]}}]},{"block":{"title":"Hands-on: Data anonymisation","type":"Title","body":"<p>In this section, we are going to follow a number of steps to demonstrate how anonymisation works in practice. In order to complete this exercise, you should download or view the dataset below.</p><p>Download the dataset here: <a href=\"https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1K5iuIn3gkzGS2HIT2pv8K4mBbO2_y_N_k0PIOTR3RXA/edit#gid=0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">#DATA NHS synthetic data</a>.csv</p>"},"components":[{"body":"<table><thead><tr><th>Site</th><th>Call date</th><th>Name</th><th>Sex</th><th>Da