pe":"Title"},"components":[{"body":"<p>NHS England recognises that data is useful. Summary data about A&amp;E departments of UK hospitals are big news. Waiting times data is <a href=\"https://www.kingsfund.org.uk/projects/urgent-emergency-care/urgent-and-emergency-care-mythbusters\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">analysed</a> and fills front pages, the TV, and the radio. Things get political very quickly.</p><div class=\"callout\"><p>But an average waiting time doesn't tell us much about what's really happening.</p></div><p>Who needed care? At what time? For what problem? And what happened as a result?</p><p>Detailed A&amp;E admissions data is far too sensitive to be made open. It is rightly afforded <a href=\"https://ico.org.uk/for-organisations/guide-to-the-general-data-protection-regulation-gdpr/lawful-basis-for-processing/special-category-data/\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">special category status within both the GDPR and The Data Protection Act 2018</a>.</p><p>Synthetic data provides a potential method through which statistically accurate data can be shared.</p><div class=\"callout\"><p>You can read more about the work of ODI Leeds and NHS England on creating synthetic A&amp;E data <a href=\"https://open-innovations.org/events/synae/\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">here</a> including detail on the <a href=\"https://open-innovations.org/blog/2019-01-24-exploring-methods-for-creating-synthetic-a-e-data\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">methodology</a>.</p></div>","properties":{"instruction":"","items":[]}}]},{"block":{"title":"Do data protection regulations apply to anonymised or synthetic data?","type":"Question"},"components":[{"properties":{"instruction":"Choose one option then select Submit.","items":[{"text":"Yes","shouldBeSelected":false},{"text":"No","shouldBeSelected":true}],"feedback":{"correct":"<p><strong>That's right!</p></strong></p><p>Once the data is anonymised, data protection regulations no longer apply and data can be shared w