 will be dependent on your dataset, your objective and most of all - the risk of re-identification.&nbsp;</p>","properties":{"instruction":"","items":[]}}]},{"block":{"title":"Synthetic data","type":"Title"},"components":[{"body":"<p>What if your objective doesn’t require you to explicitly use personal data? The example above is synthetic data - that is, it’s been created. It’s not real.&nbsp;</p><p>A synthetic dataset contains many of the statistical patterns of an original dataset, but does not refer to identifiable individuals (for example it contains fictional people), thereby reducing the risk of re-identification. Intuitively, it is easy to see how this could enable the sharing or open release of data similar to very sensitive data, but with less risk of data protection infringement attached to it.</p><div class=\"callout\"><p><strong>Explore some case studies in synthetic data below</strong></p></div>","properties":{"instruction":"","items":[]}}]},{"block":{"title":"Synthetic data as training data for AI","type":"Title"},"components":[{"body":"<p>One problem that can arise with AI systems is a lack of training data. For example, to train an AI to recognise defects from images of objects; it is first necessary to have images of defective objects. Rather than gather real world images, one potential is to create a synthetic dataset of objects with defects (ie. using CAD software).&nbsp;</p><p>This can then form 90% of the training data with real world data used to test accuracy. Additionally, the dataset can be created under controlled conditions, minimising a number of biases and speeding up collection.</p>","properties":{"instruction":"","items":[]}},{"properties":{"instruction":"","items":[]}}]},{"block":{"title":"Diagnosing the NHS: SynÆ","type":"Title"},"components":[{"body":"<p>NHS England recognises that data is useful. Summary data about A&amp;E departments of UK hospitals are big news. Waiting times data is <a href=\"https://www.kingsfund.org.uk/projects/urgent-emergency-care/urgent-and-emergency-care-mythbusters\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">analysed</a> and fills front pages, the TV, and the radio. Things get political very quickly.</p><div class=\"callout\"><p>But an average waiting time doesn't tell us much about what's really happening.</p></div><p>Who needed care? At what time? For what problem? And what happened as a result?</p><p>Detailed A&amp;E admissions data is far too sensitive to be made open. It is rightly afforded <a href=\"https://ico.org.uk/for-organisations/guide-to-the-general-data-protection-regulation-gdpr/lawful-basis-for-processing/special-category-data/\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">special category status within both the GDPR and The Data Protection Act 2018</a>.</p><p>Synthetic data provides a potential method through which statistically accurate data can be shared.</p><div class=\"callout\"><p>You can read more about the work of ODI Leeds and NHS England on creating synthetic A&amp;E data <a href=\"https://open-innovations.org/events/synae/\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">here</a> including detail on the <a href=\"https://open-innovations.org/blog/2019-01-24-exploring-methods-for-creating-synthetic-a-e-data\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">methodology</a>.</p></div>","properties":{"instruction":"","items":[]}}]},{"block":{"title":"Do data protection regulations apply to anonymised or synthetic data?","type":"Question"},"components":[{"properties":{"instruction":"Choose one option then select Submit.","items":[{"text":"Yes","shouldBeSelected":false},{"text":"No","shouldBeSelected":true}],"feedback":{"correct":"<p><strong>That's right!</p></strong></p><p>Once the data is anonymised, data protection regulations no longer apply and data can be shared with others safely, even outside the geographical boundaries that may be imposed by data protection regulations.</p><p>However, this does not mean that the retention, use and sharing (or not sharing) of the data will be e