hough Profession is not personal data, we do run the risk of making an individual identifiable if we’re not careful - for example, how many mayors exist in any given town? The same could be said for post code. The risk is low in densely populated areas, but for more rural addresses it may not be unusual for a post code to only have a small number of addresses, possibly only one.&nbsp;</p>"}}}]},{"block":{"title":"STEP 4: Anonymise the data","type":"Title"},"components":[{"body":"<p>There are several ways to anonymise data including Suppression, Randomisation, Generalisation and Pseudonymisation. For the purposes of this module, we’re going to focus on Suppression and Generalisation.</p>","properties":{"instruction":"Select the headings to find out more.","items":[{"title":"Suppression","body":"<p>Suppression simply involves removing data from the dataset, such as any identifier or person’s name. Suppression is best applied on any direct identifiers. It is important to carefully consider the use cases before simply deleting data, otherwise, the overuse of suppression is highly likely to reduce the utility of data.</p>"},{"title":"Generalisation","body":"<p>This approach consists of generalising or diluting the attributes of data by modifying the respective scale or order of magnitude (that is, a region rather than a city, a month rather than a week).</p><p>While generalisation can be effective to prevent re-identification, it does not allow effective anonymisation in all cases; in particular, it requires specific and sophisticated quantitative approaches to prevent linkability and inference.</p>"},{"title":"Randomisation","body":"<p>This method adds randomness to data while keeping it useful for analysis by maintaining statistical significance. For instance, in age data, randomisation means adding a random number to each person's age. This way, data stays useful but doesn't reveal exact details about individuals.&nbsp;</p>"},{"title":"Pseudonymisation ","body":"<p>This involves replacing sensitive data with pseudonyms or fake identifiers. Unlike other techniques, where data is made completely unidentifiable, pseudonymisation allows for reversible transformation. This means that the original data can be linked back to the pseudonyms using a special key or method known only to authorised users.&nbsp;</p><p>Pseudonymisation helps protect personal data while still allowing for data analysis and processing, making it a useful approach for balancing privacy and data usability. However, it’s important to note that pseudonymised data carries a higher risk of re-identification and therefore may not necessarily be the most appropriate practice for protecting an individual's privacy.&nbsp;</p>"}]}}]},{"block":{"title":"Application to our example dataset","type":"Title"},"components":[{"body":"<p><strong>If we were to suppress (remove) all the personal data, then this dataset would not be useful to fulfil any of our objectives. So, we need to consider other methods.</strong></p><p>It may be useful to consider what needs to be kept to fulfill our objectives:</p><table><thead><tr><th>Personal data field</th><th>Objective #1</th><th>Objective #2</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Name</td><td>No</td><td>No</td></tr><tr><td>Sex</td><td>Potentially useful</td><td>Potentially useful</td></tr><tr><td>Date of birth</td><td>No</td><td>Yes</td></tr><tr><td>Address</td><td>Yes</td><td>Yes</td></tr><tr><td>Postcode</td><td>Yes</td><td>Yes</td></tr></tbody></table><p>From this, it is clear we can suppress the person’s name.</p><p>At this point, while the person is not directly identifiable, a combination of the other characteristics will allow people to be re-identified easily, therefore we haven’t finished yet.</p><p>The next most identifiable piece of information is probably the exact address, given that only a small number of people will live at a single address. We can aggregate this information to anonymise it:</p><table><thead><tr><th>Address (original)</th><th>Address (anonymised)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>12 Penn Street, Barking, London</td><td>Barking, London</td></tr><tr><td>27 Penelope Drive, Eastbourne</td><td>Eastbourne</td></tr><tr><td>19 Barber Close, Matlock, Derby</td><td>Matlock, Derby</td></tr><tr><td>27 Diagon Alley, Tower Hamlets, London</td><td>Tower Hamlets, London</td></tr><tr><td>155 Mount Park, Shrewsbury</td><td>Shrewsbury</td></tr><tr><td>17 Prestige Place, Ringwood</td><td>Ringwood</td></tr></tbody></table><p>We could also do the same with the postcode, removing the last three digits to just identify regions in a city, for example, W1, W2, etc.</p><p>Aggregation can also be used to translate the date of birth into an age range, for example, 0–18, 19–69, 70–120.</p><div class=\"table-container\"><table><thead><tr><th>Date of birth (original)</th><th>Age band (anonymised)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>2005-06-03</td><td>0–18 years</td></tr><tr><td>1949-11-10</td><td>70–120 years</td></tr><tr><td>1981-10-08</td><td>19–69 years</td></tr><tr><td>1946-02-28</td><td>70–120 years</td></tr><tr><td>1922-03-15</td><td>70–120 years</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div><p>By applying anonymisation techniques we are able to ensure that the data shared complies with the law but maintains its utility. By recognising what personal data is contained within our datasets, we can decide on the appropriate anonymisation technique that enables us to meet our objectives.</p><p>In this example, in order to meet our objective:</p><p>“to report back on high-level Covid infection statistics across counties in the UK”,</p><p>we can apply anonymisation using suppression and simply remove identifiable data (i.e., the personal data) and generalise other data points by simplifying their location-based data.</p></div><p>Apply anonymisation techniques to the NHS Synthetic Dataset. When you’re ready, review the model answer below.</p>","properties":{"instruction":"","items":[]}}]},{"block":{"title":"Reviewing the model","type":"Title"},"components":[{"body":"<table><thead><tr><th>Site</th><th>Call date</th><th>Sex</th><th>age range (years)</th><th>Address</th><th>Postcode</th><th>Profession</th><th>Severity (1=High)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>111</td><td>12/03/2022</td><td>F</td><td>0-18</td><td>Barking, London</td><td>IG11</td><td>Student</td><td>35</td></tr><tr><td>111</td><td>18/03/2022</td><td>F</td><td>70-120</td><td>Eastbourne</td><td>BN20</td><td>Retired</td><td>3</td></tr><tr><td>111</td><td>18/03/2022</td><td>M</td><td>19-69</td><td>Matlock, Derby</td><td>DE4</td><td>Gardener</td><td>90</td></tr><tr><td>999</td><td>18/03/2022</td><td>M</td><td>70-120</td><td>Tower Hamlets, London</td><td>E1</td><td>Professor</td><td>1</td></tr><tr><td>999</td><td>14/04/2022</td><td>M</td><td>70-120</td><td>Shrewbury</td><td>SY1</td><td>Retired</td><td>2</td></tr><tr><td>999</td><td>15/04/2022</td><td>F</td><td>19-69</td><td>Ringwood</td><td>BH24</td><td>Councillor</td><td>6</td></tr></tbody></table><p>To anonymise the dataset we have undertaken the following activities:</p>","properties":{"instruction":"Select the headings to find out more.","items":[{"title":"Suppressed the Name","body":"<p>&nbsp;(we’ve removed the column entirely)</p>"},{"title":"Generalised the address","body":"<p>by removing street names and home numbers, as well as the post code which now identifies an area of the UK, but not a specific street.&nbsp;</p>"},{"title":"Generalised the profession","body":"<p>You’ll see that only the job role of the mayor has been updated. Student, Retired, Gardener and Professor were deemed to be sufficiently broad. However, it is likely there will only be one mayor in an area and therefore this may lead to identification. You may have chosen to generalise these job roles, or remove them entirely as they are not directly related to our objective.&nbsp;</p>"},{"title":"Generalised the date of birth","body":"<p>In this example, we’ve used 0-18, 19-69 and 70-120. These are very broad categorisations. We could expand these into further groups to support a more granular analysis.&nbsp;</p>"}]}}]},{"block":{},"components":[{"body":"<p>There’s not necessarily a right or wrong answer when it comes to anonymisation techniques. The amount of anonymisation applied, and which technique is applied will be dependent on your dataset, your objective and most of all - the risk of re-identification.&nbsp;</p>","properties":{"instruction":"","items":[]}}]},{"block":{"title":"Synthetic data","type":"Title"},"components":[{"body":"<p>What if your objective doesn’t require you to explicitly use personal data? The example above is synthetic data - that is, it’s been created. It’s not real.&nbsp;</p><p>A synthetic dataset contains many of the statistical patterns of an original dataset, but does not refer to identifiable individuals (for example it contains fictional people), thereby reducing the risk of re-identification. Intuitively, it is easy to see how this could enable the sharing or open release of data similar to very sensitive data, but with less risk of data protection infringement attached to it.</p><div class=\"callout\"><p><strong>Explore some case studies in synthetic data below</strong></p></div>","properties":{"instruction":"","items":[]}}]},{"block":{"title":"Synthetic data as training data for AI","type":"Title"},"components":[{"body":"<p>One problem that can arise with AI systems is a lack of training data. For example, to train an AI to recognise defects from images of objects; it is first necessary to have images of defective objects. Rather than gather real world images, one potential is to create a synthetic dataset of objects with defects (ie. using CAD software).&nbsp;</p><p>This can then form 90% of the training data with real world data used to test accuracy. Additionally, the dataset can be created under controlled conditions, minimising a number of biases and speeding up collection.</p>","properties":{"instruction":"","items":[]}},{"properties":{"instruction":"","items":[]}}]},{"block":{"title":"Diagnosing the NHS: SynÆ","type":"Title"},"components":[{"body":"<p>NHS England recognises that data is useful. Summary data about A&amp;E departments of UK hospitals are big news. Waiting times data is <a href=\"https://www.kingsfund.org.uk/projects/urgent-emergency-care/urgent-and-emergency-care-mythbusters\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">analysed</a> and fills front pages, the TV, and the radio. Things get political very quickly.</p><div class=\"callout\"><p>But an average waiting time doesn't tell us much about what's really happening.</p></div><p>Who needed care? At what time? For what problem? And what happened as a result?</p><p>Detailed A&amp;E admissions data is far too sensitive to be made open. It is rightly afforded <a href=\"https://ico.org.uk/for-organisations/guide-to-the-general-data-protection-regulation-gdpr/lawful-basis-for-processing/special-category-data/\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">special category status within both the GDPR and The Data Protection Act 2018</a>.</p><p>Synthetic data provides a potential method through which statistically accurate data can be shared.</p><div class=\"callout\"><p>You can read more about the work of ODI Leeds and NHS England on creating synthetic A&amp;E data <a href=\"https://open-innovations.org/events/synae/\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">here</a> including detail on the <a href=\"https://open-innovations.org/blog/2019-01-24-exploring-methods-for-creating-synthetic-a-e-data\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">methodology</a>.</p></div>","properties":{"instruction":"","items":[]}}]},{"block":{"title":"Do data protection regulations apply to anonymised or synthetic data?","type":"Question"},"components":[{"properties":{"instruction":"Choose one option then select Submit.","items":[{"text":"Yes","shouldBeSelected":false},{"text":"No","shouldBeSelected":true}],"feedback":{"correct":"<p><strong>That's right!</p></strong></p><p>Once 