als (for example it contains fictional people), thereby reducing the risk of re-identification. Intuitively, it is easy to see how this could enable the sharing or open release of data similar to very sensitive data, but with less risk of data protection infringement attached to it.</p><div class=\"callout\"><p><strong>Explore some case studies in synthetic data below</strong></p></div>","properties":{"instruction":"","items":[]}}]},{"block":{"title":"Synthetic data as training data for AI","type":"Title"},"components":[{"body":"<p>One problem that can arise with AI systems is a lack of training data. For example, to train an AI to recognise defects from images of objects; it is first necessary to have images of defective objects. Rather than gather real world images, one potential is to create a synthetic dataset of objects with defects (ie. using CAD software).&nbsp;</p><p>This can then form 90% of the training data with real world data used to test accuracy. Additionally, the dataset can be created under controlled conditions, minimising a number of biases and speeding up collection.</p>","properties":{"instruction":"","items":[]}},{"properties":{"instruction":"","items":[]}}]},{"block":{"title":"Diagnosing the NHS: SynÆ","type":"Title"},"components":[{"body":"<p>NHS England recognises that data is useful. Summary data about A&amp;E departments of UK hospitals are big news. Waiting times data is <a href=\"https://www.kingsfund.org.uk/projects/urgent-emergency-care/urgent-and-emergency-care-mythbusters\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">analysed</a> and fills front pages, the TV, and the radio. Things get political very quickly.</p><div class=\"callout\"><p>But an average waiting time doesn't tell us much about what's really happening.</p></div><p>Who needed care? At what time? For what problem? And what happened as a result?</p><p>Detailed A&amp;E admissions data is far too sensitive to be made open. It is rightly afforded <a href=\"https://ico.org.uk/for-organisations/guide-to-the-general-data-protection-regulation-gdpr/lawful-basis-for-processing/special-category-data/\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">special category status within both the GDPR and The Data Protection Act 2018</a>.</p><p>Synthetic data provides a potential method through which statistically accurate data can be shared.</p><div class=\"callout\"><p>You can read more about the work of ODI Leeds and NHS England on creating synthetic A&amp;E data <a href=\"https://open-innovations.org/events/synae/\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">here</a> including detail on the <a href=\"https://open-innovations.org/blog/2019-01-24-exploring-methods-for-creating-synthetic-a-e-data\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">methodology</a>.</p></div>","properties":{"instruction":"","items":[]}}]},{"block":{"title":"Do data protection regulations apply to anonymised or synthetic data?","type":"Question"},"components":[{"properties":{"instruction":"Choose one option then select Submit.","items":[{"text":"Yes","shouldBeSelected":false},{"text":"No","shouldBeSelected":true}],"feedback":{"correct":"<p><strong>That's right!</p></strong></p><p>Once the data is anonymised, data protection regulations no longer apply and data can be shared with others safely, even outside the geographical boundaries that may be imposed by data protection regulations.</p><p>However, this does not mean that the retention, use and sharing (or not sharing) of the data will be ethical, even if it is legal.</p>","incorrect":"<p><strong>Are you sure about that?</p></strong></p><p>Once the data is anonymised, data protection regulations no longer apply and data can be shared with others safely, even outside the geographical boundaries that may be imposed by data protection regulations.</p><p>However, this does not mean that the retention, use and sharing (or not sharing) of the data will be ethical, even if it is legal.</p>"}}},{"properties":{"instruction":"","items":[]}}]},{"block":{"title":"STEP 5: Testing resilience","type":"Title"},"components":[{"body":"<div class=\"heading-with-rule\"><p>Application to our example dataset</p></div><div class=\"padded-callout\"><p><strong>Remember the questions:</strong></p><ol><li>Is it possible to single out an individual?</li><li>Is it possible to link records relating to an individual using data already available to people?</li><li>Can information be inferred concerning an individual within the same dataset?</li></ol></div><p>Let’s apply these to the dataset:</p><div><div><table><thead><tr><th>Feature</th><th>Example value</th><th>Q1</th><th>Q2</th><th>Q3</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Site Type</td><td>111,999</td><td>N</td><td>N</td><td>N</td></tr><tr><td>Call date</td><td>2020-03-19</td><td>N</td><td>N</td><td>N</td></tr><tr><td>Name</td><td>Joe Bloggs</td><td colspan=\"3\">REMOVED FROM DATA</td></tr><tr><td>Date of Birth</td><td>2005-06-03</td><td colspan=\"3\">REMOVED FROM DATA</td></tr><tr><td>Age Band</td><td>0–18,19–69,70–120</td><td>N</td><td>N</td><td>N</td></tr><tr><td>Town/City</td><td>Matlock</td><td>N</td><td>Potentially in some sparsely populated areas. Classifying as low risk.</td><td>N</td></tr><tr><td>Postcode area</td><td>IG11</td><td>N</td><td>Potentially in some sparsely populated areas. Classifying as low risk.</td><td>N</td></tr><tr><td>Profession</td><td>Student, Counselor</td><td>N</td><td>N</td><td>N</td></tr></tbody></table></div></div>","properties":{"instruction":"","items":[]}}]},{"block":{"title":"STEP 6: Write a plan to mitigate risk","type":"Title"},"components":[{"body":"<p>Rather than apply and plan to mitigate risk regarding our dataset, we applied this step to the whole of this guide. The guide was reviewed internally by senior members of the ODI team prior to publication to ensure our advice is both accurate and set in the right tone that provides the right balance between risk and utility.</p><p>Although the dataset was synthetic, some of the data points, e.g. postcodes, are realist